  "prompt": "Why did the government of India introduced a 2000 rupee note instead of a new 1000 rupee note?",
  "response": "The Indian government introduced the 2000 rupee note in November 2016 as part of its demonetization initiative. The primary goal was to replace the existing 500 and 1000 rupee notes that were being demonetized to curb corruption, black money, and counterfeit currency.\n\nHere are some key reasons for introducing the 2000 rupee note:\n\n1. **High-Value Transactions**: The introduction of the 2000 rupee note was aimed at facilitating high-value transactions, which would be more cumbersome with lower denomination notes.\n\n2. **Cost Efficiency**: Printing higher denomination notes like the 2000 rupee note is more cost-effective for the government compared to printing more lower denomination notes to cover the same value.\n\n3. **Transition Ease**: During the demonetization process, the availability of a higher denomination note helped in the transition by allowing individuals to exchange old currency notes for fewer new notes, simplifying the logistics and easing the burden on banks.\n\n4. **Cash Economy**: India has a large cash-based economy, and higher denomination notes can help in managing large amounts of cash more efficiently for both individuals and businesses.\n\n5. **Immediate Availability**: Introducing the 2000 rupee note provided an immediate solution to the liquidity crunch caused by the demonetization of the 500 and 1000 rupee notes.\n\nThe introduction of the 2000 rupee note was a strategic decision to address the immediate needs of the economy while working towards long-term goals of reducing cash dependency and increasing digital transactions.",
